{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774373662,"nonce":"ZeggR6mFoLk6c4CY06w/0Sqz4XM=","message":"## Run 6: Perturbation strength sweep (pert_std = 0, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20)\n\n### Training results (standard backprop, running_cost loss, 10k batches)\n\n| pert_std | Loss | Ep error | Lat dev (eval scale=1) | Peak vel | SISU vel | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | 690 | 0.456 | (invalid — no training gusts) | 5.6 | -11.2% | Diverged |\n| 1 | 2.9 | 0.007 | 0.013 | 3.33 | -0.3% | Converged |\n| 2 | 422 | 0.693 | 0.383 | — | — | **Diverged** |\n| 5 | 10.3 | 0.078 | — | — | — | Mediocre |\n| 10 | ~3.0 | 0.005 | 0.006 | 3.3 | +0.0% | Converged |\n| 20 | ~3.0 | 0.005 | 0.008 | 3.3 | +0.4% | Converged |\n\n### Key finding: non-monotonic stability\n\npert_std=2 and pert_std=5 FAIL or underperform, while pert_std=10 and pert_std=20 converge well. This suggests a \"valley of instability\" in the optimization landscape at moderate perturbation strengths. The model can handle either no perturbations or very strong ones, but moderate perturbations create an optimization challenge.\n\npert_std=10 and 20 produce comparable robustness to pert_std=1, with slightly better endpoint accuracy.\n\n### Interpretation\n\nThe non-monotonic pattern suggests the perturbation amplitude interacts with the loss landscape in a complex way. At pert_std=2-5, the perturbation is strong enough to disrupt gradient signals but not strong enough to force the network into a clearly robust strategy. At pert_std=10-20, the perturbation dominates and the network is forced to learn robust control.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}